		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cincinnati</placeName> <date>22<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> Mar 5609</date></p>
			<p>Revd Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I hand you Letter 5 on the Union&#44; being in continuation<lb/> of the exposition of the divine plan for the government of<lb/> man. Have the goodness to notify its receipt by you</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">The portion of the exposition now sent was rather difficult to<lb/> treat. I should like to have your opinion whether I have<lb/> succeeded or not in expounding the meaning of the Tree<lb/> of Life. The Tree of the Knowledge of Good &#38; Evil. The<lb/> sentences pronounced upon <persName>Adam</persName> and <persName>Eve</persName> and upon the<lb/> serpent &#38;c &#38;c At the conclusion of the letter I have inti&#61;<lb/>&#61;mated that my labours on the Union would cease for a<lb/> time&#59; my reasons for which are there.&#8212;The meeting takes<lb/> place on the <date>11<hi rend="sup">th</hi>&#44; June</date>&#44; the letter now sent will just be in<lb/> time to be published before&#44; and as in my two letters 1 &#38; 2 I<lb/> have given my opinion on the principles on which to base the<lb/> Union and likewise on the mode on which the deliberations<lb/> of the meeting should be conducted&#44; and you have very ably<lb/> pointed out some of the objects that might engage the<lb/> attention of the union when formed&#44; there is plenty of matter<lb/> for the present occasion&#44; for I thought and do still think that it<lb/> was sufficient to support in general terms what constitute the<lb/> duties obligatory on Israelites&#44; and that the proposed meeting<lb/> would have nothing to do except to decide whether a Union</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>was expedient or not for fulfilling those duties and if it was<lb/> decided in the affirmative then to revert to steps for<lb/> inducing the congregations to take the matter into their<lb/> hands and found the Union&#44; and it would belong to the<lb/> Body appointed to carry out its objects to promote <add>&#63;</add><lb/> to fulfill the duties. I cannot say I understand in what<lb/> light the proposed meeting is to be viewed. By the circular<lb/> and what some here say it would appear it is to form<lb/> the Union at once and proceed to legislate upon measures<lb/> still this does not appear possible if I am rightly informed<lb/> that no sending the delegates the congregation mean nothing<lb/> but that they should have representatives at a meeting to be<lb/> purely of a suggestive and <sic>advisary</sic> character and not at<lb/> all legislative. With the crude notions of some and the<lb/> small intelligence evinced by others how to handle a measure<lb/> so important as a union of the congregations&#44; I shall regret<lb/> but certainly shall not be surprised that the whole prove<lb/> a failure I remain</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Revd Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Yrs. very truly</p>
          <p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee> <hi rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">A A. Lindo</persName></hi></p>
			<p>I have just discovered an error in the second line of the<lb/> concluding paragraph of my letter 2. page 612 of the<lb/> occident for <date>march</date>&#44; the word &#8220;Spiritual&#8221; having been<lb/> substituted for &#8220;perpetual&#8221; which I will thank you to take<lb/> on early opportunity to notice. Yrs <persName role="author">AAL</persName></p>

